  "local_port": 55292,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do colleges look at community college transcript (along with the high school transcript) for undergraduates?",
  "response": "When evaluating undergraduate applicants who have attended community college, admissions committees at four-year institutions typically consider both the high school and community college transcripts. Here's how they generally approach this process:\n\n### 1. **Holistic Review**\n   - Colleges often use a holistic review process, meaning they consider the full context of your academic journey, including your high school performance, community college coursework, and any other relevant factors (e.g., extracurriculars, essays, letters of recommendation).\n\n### 2. **Academic Performance in Community College**\n   - **GPA:** Your community college GPA is a key indicator of your academic readiness. A strong GPA demonstrates your ability to succeed in college-level coursework.\n   - **Coursework:** Admissions committees assess the rigor and relevance of your community college courses. Completing transferable general education courses or prerequisites for your intended major can be particularly advantageous.\n   - **Trends:** An upward trend in grades or consistent high performance can strengthen your application.\n\n### 3. **High School Transcript**\n   - Your high school transcript is still important, especially if you didn't complete many community college credits or if you're applying as a freshman transfer (with fewer than 30\u201360 college credits).\n   - They\u2019ll look at your high school GPA, class rank (if available), and the rigor of your high school courses (e.g., honors, AP, IB).\n\n### 4. **Transfer Credit Evaluation**\n   - If you\u2019re applying as a transfer student, the college will evaluate which community college credits are transferable toward your intended degree program. This can affect how many credits you\u2019ll need to complete at the four-year institution.\n\n### 5. **Course Alignment with Intended Major**\n   - Admissions committees will check if your community college coursework aligns with your intended major. For example, completing intro-level courses in your field of interest can show preparedness.\n\n### 6. **Dual Enrollment or College Credit in High School**\n   - If you earned community college credits through dual enrollment or early college programs while in high school, these grades will often be considered alongside your high school transcript.\n\n### 7. **Extracurriculars and Context**\n   - Admissions officers also look at what you were doing outside of the classroom during your time in community college (e.g., work, internships, clubs, volunteer work) to gauge your engagement and leadership skills.\n\n### 8. **Standardized Test Scores (if required)**\n   - Some colleges may still require SAT or ACT scores, especially if you\u2019re applying as a freshman or have limited community college credits. Check the specific requirements of the schools you\u2019re applying to.\n\n### 9. **Essays and Personal Statements**\n   - Your essays can provide context for your academic journey, including any challenges you\u2019ve overcome or why you chose to start at a community college.\n\n### 10. **Letters of Recommendation**\n   - Letters from community college professors or advisors can provide insight into your academic abilities and character.\n\n### Key Takeaways:\n- A strong community college transcript can significantly enhance your application, especially if it shows academic growth and completion of relevant coursework.\n- Your high school transcript remains important, particularly if you have fewer community college credits.\n- Admissions committees value consistency, rigor, and alignment with your intended major.\n\nEach college has its own policies, so it\u2019s essential to research the specific requirements of the schools you\u2019re interested in. If you\u2019re unsure, reach out to the admissions office for clarification.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
